Mitch: 

OK - Here is the problem 2 over 1 players face: 
If you open 1@H or 1@S in first or second seat, and partner responds 1NT, you may not pass
Period. 
Pard could have any of a couple of dozen different hand patterns, including support, 
or perhaps a void in your suit.
Your first priority for rebidding after 1@S - 1N is to limit your hand's strength
Recall that a minimum opener has a maximum of 15 HCP, and an "invitational" hand has 16-18; 
a strong opener has 19-21 points

So your first rebid helps decide which range you are in:
A 2-level bid below 2 of your major shows a minimum - to - invitational hand
Rebidding 2 of your major says you have a ^*B6-card^*N suit and a minimum hand.

Example: 1@S - 1NT / and you have     KJ10xxx, Kxx, Ax, Qx
rebid 2@S

Next: If you have opened 1@S and you have 4 hearts (or more) you will usually bid 2@H with a minimum
There are exceptions - but for now, we won't worry about them

If you do not have 6 spades or 4 heart when you open 1@S, you will bid your longer minor suit
Sometimes, that will be a 3 card suit. Example  KJ10xx, Axx, xxx, Ax
Even tho it's very, very ugly, the correct rebid is 2@D - responder will know you may have a cruddy suit.

OK - how many points does that 2@D bid promise? 
You may have as many as 15 points.|
